<HEAD>U.S. Military Authorities Restrict Soviet Eskimo Delegation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SISIMUIT, Greenland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military authorities restricted
the movements of a Soviet delegation taking part in an Eskimo
conference, participants were told <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military told the 18 Soviet delegates to remain in
their hotel during a <DATE>Sunday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> stop at Soendre Stroemfjord, a
<LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> base in <LOCATION>Greenland</LOCATION>, said the Soviets and the conference
president. Delegates from <LOCATION>Alaska</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> were allowed to move
around the base.
   Canadian <PERSON>Mary Simon</PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION>Inuit Circumpolar
Conference</ORGANIZATION>, said the incident was unfortunate.
   ``The Soviets are equal participants in our congress and should
have been treated that way. ''
   The Soviets are attending the conference for the first time. The
other delegates are from <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Alaska</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Greenland</LOCATION>. The 500
participants represent the world's more than 100,000 Arctic natives.
   <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> was the second day of the weeklong conference, being
held in <LOCATION>Sisimiut</LOCATION>, a town of 5,000 people on <LOCATION>Greenland</LOCATION>'s east coast.
   <PERSON>Ms. Simon</PERSON>, an Inuit from <LOCATION>Quebec</LOCATION>, told the conference that
self-government remains a vitally important question for the Inuit
_ or Eskimo _ people.
   <LOCATION>Greenland</LOCATION> has enjoyed home rule since <DATE>1979</DATE>. But in <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>, the
issue is one of acute concern, and negotiations with the Canadian
government are proceeding slowly, <PERSON>Ms. Simon</PERSON> said.
   In <LOCATION>Alaska</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Native Land Claims Settlement</ORGANIZATION> of <DATE>1971</DATE> did nothing
to address the issue of self-government, she said.
</TEXT>
