<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Brian Mulroney; ... changes 'long overdue'  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  CANADA; GOVERNMENT; CHANGE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Prime Minister Brian Mulroney proposed changes to the constitution today that
would recognize Quebec as a "distinct society," provide for an elected Senate
and allow Indians and Inuit self-government.;   The purpose of the
constitutional overhaul is "to build a stronger, more prosperous Canada where
all Canadians can feel at home," the Conservative prime minister told the
House of Commons.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'DISTINCT SOCIETY' IN QUEBEC CALLED FOR IN CANADA
PLAN  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "These changes add up to a renewal that is long overdue. And renewal is
what Canadians everywhere seek for our country -- not confrontation, not
division, not rupture.";   The "distinct society" proposal is likely to be the
most controversial. A similar idea is what sank an effort at constitutional
reform 15 months ago. That package, known as the <ORGANIZATION>Meech Lake</ORGANIZATION> accords, failed to
win the necessary unanimous ratification of all 10 Canadian provinces.;  
<LOCATION>Quebec</LOCATION> viewed the failure of <ORGANIZATION>Meech Lake</ORGANIZATION> as a rejection by English <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> and
the provincial government went ahead with measures calling for a referendum on
sovereignty by <DATE>October 1992</DATE> if a new deal isn't forthcoming.;   <ORGANIZATION>Mulroney</ORGANIZATION>'s
proposal includes a distinct society provision in both the Charter of Rights
and Freedoms, <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Bill of Rights</ORGANIZATION>, and a new "<LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> clause" to the
constitution which defines what makes <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION> what it is.;   "I am sure
Quebecers will see in today's proposal the possibility of achieving the
fundamental reform that <LOCATION>Quebec</LOCATION> needs to evolve as a distinct society within
<LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>," <PERSON>Mulroney</PERSON> said.;   French-speaking <LOCATION>Quebec</LOCATION>, home to nearly 7 million of
<LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>'s 26 million people, long has felt under linguistic and cultural siege
by the English Canadians on all sides.;   Constitutional Affairs Minister <PERSON>Joe
Clark</PERSON> has said that "distinct society" only recognizes constitutionally what
has been the reality since before confederation in 1867.;   The <LOCATION>Quebec</LOCATION>
provincial government of Premier <PERSON>Robert Bourassa</PERSON> has said it would have no
immediate reaction to the proposals.;   Liberal Leader <PERSON>Jean Chretien</PERSON>, in his
speech to the Commons, welcomed the principles for reform outlined by
<PERSON>Mulroney</PERSON>, but stopped short of endorsing the package. "Indeed, our first
impression is that the proposals of the government need a great deal of work,"
<PERSON>Chretien</PERSON> said.;   Outside the <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> chamber, <PERSON>Chretien</PERSON> said the Liberals "will
study the proposition. We will make some suggestions.";   <PERSON>Audrey McLaughlin</PERSON>,
leader of the New Democratic Party, was distressed that the proposals "made no
mention of the need to entrench social rights" in the constitution.;   The
<PERSON>Mulroney</PERSON> government has asked opposition parties to give the measures a chance
and not reject them immediately.;   The package of proposals will be turned
over to a joint committee of the <ORGANIZATION>House of Commons</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> which will tour
the country seeking public comment. Its report is due by <DATE>Feb. 28.</DATE>;   The
measures are expected to change the <DATE>1982</DATE> constitution, which <LOCATION>Quebec</LOCATION> never
signed but is bound by.;   The proposals provide for an elected <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION>, which
is now appointed by the government. Provincial representation would be decided
later. The elected <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> would have a limited veto power over legislation.;  
<PERSON>Mulroney</PERSON> said there is a new commitment to <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>'s 500,000 Indians and Inuit
-- or Eskimos -- to give them self-government within 10 years.;   <LOCATION>Ottawa</LOCATION> is
seeking more power in the proposals to tear down barriers to interprovincial
trade.  </TEXT>
