<HEAD>Trek to Reunify Eskimo Cultures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet-American dog sledding team announced
plans <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> to symbolically break the ice between Siberian and
Alaskan Eskimos during a 1,200-mile goodwill trek that will include
the first sanctioned crossing of the <LOCATION>Bering Strait</LOCATION> since <DATE>1948</DATE>.
   Ten men and two women, comprising six Soviets and six Americans,
plan to depart <DATE>March 1</DATE> from <LOCATION>Anadyr</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Siberia</LOCATION>, on a two-month journey
visiting 30 native settlements along an old Arctic trade route.
   The expedition is an attempt to call attention to the common
cultural heritage of the indigenous peoples of the <LOCATION>Bering</LOCATION> region,
expedition co-leader <PERSON>Paul Schurke</PERSON>, 33, of <LOCATION>Minneapolis</LOCATION>, said at a
news conference at the <ORGANIZATION>Russian Tea Room</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Manhattan</LOCATION>.
   ``Some of the team members have relatives on the other side,''
<PERSON>Schurke</PERSON> said, so it could be a very emotional experience.
   Because visitors are rare in villages so close to the top of the
world, he predicted that the expedition would be met with
``spontaneous celebrations and jamborees'' and that schools would be
let out so that the children could ski along with the team for a
while.
   A veteran of Arctic travel who made an unassisted trek to the
<LOCATION>North Pole</LOCATION> in <DATE>1986</DATE>, <PERSON>Schurke</PERSON> said the journey was ``an opportunity to
combine my interest in travel in the north with playing a part in
the process of improving Soviet-American relations.''
   Speaking through an interpreter, Soviet co-leader <PERSON>Dmitry Shparo</PERSON>,
47, of <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION>, praised <ORGANIZATION>Du Pont Co.</ORGANIZATION>, the major American corporate
sponsor of the <ORGANIZATION>Bering Bridge Expedition</ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON>Shparo</PERSON> also put in a plug
for the main Soviet sponsors, Pravda's youth newspaper, the tourist
bureau known as Sputnik and <ORGANIZATION>Novosti</ORGANIZATION>, a news agency.
   Although he is a mathematics professor at <LOCATION>Moscow</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Institute of
Steel</ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION>Alloys</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Shparo</PERSON> is best known as a writer and adventurer.
In <DATE>1979</DATE>, he won the <LOCATION>Soviet Union</LOCATION>'s highest honor, the Order of
<ORGANIZATION>Lenin</ORGANIZATION>, for successfully leading a ski expedition to the <LOCATION>North Pole</LOCATION>.
Last year, he was a member of a Soviet-Canadian trek across the
polar ice cap from the <ORGANIZATION>USSR</ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION>Canada</LOCATION>.
   Sen. <PERSON>Frank Murkowski</PERSON>, <LOCATION>R-Alaska</LOCATION>, who also attended the news
conference, called the <LOCATION>Bering</LOCATION> Bridge Expedition ``another step
toward melting the ice curtain.''
   <PERSON>Murkowski</PERSON> noted that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> government is working on a new
treaty with the Soviets that would permit American Eskimos to visit
and trade with their counterparts in <LOCATION>Siberia</LOCATION> without visas.
   In <DATE>1938</DATE>, the two countries signed an agreement that regularized
travel in the <LOCATION>Bering</LOCATION> region, but that agreement was abrogated in
<DATE>1948</DATE> during the iciest days of the Cold War.
   In the spirit of adventure diplomacy, the team hopes a new
agreement can be signed at a ceremony at the U.S.-Soviet border
around <DATE>April 1</DATE>.
</TEXT>
