<HEAD>Greenland Premier Calls Election in Wake of Political Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>Greenland</LOCATION> Premier <PERSON>Jonathan Motzfeldt</PERSON>
has called for <DATE>March</DATE> elections following a scandal arising from
allegations that Cabinet ministers misused public funds, news
reports said <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   Opponents of Motzfeldt's socialist government claim to have
documents to show that government members, including the premier,
spent state money on lavish meals for the party faithful, the
<LOCATION>Greenland</LOCATION> newspaper <PERSON>Atuagagdliutit</PERSON> said.
   Motzfeldt, a pastor of the <ORGANIZATION>Greenland Lutheran Church</ORGANIZATION>, has held
the premiership since <LOCATION>Greenland</LOCATION> won partial independence from
<LOCATION>Denmark</LOCATION> in <DATE>1979</DATE>.
   About 53,000 people reside in <LOCATION>Greenland</LOCATION>, which has 840,000
square miles of territory, about <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of it ice-covered.
   Motzfeldt allegedly used <MONEY>$9,000</MONEY> of taxpayers' money on a
luxurious dinner in support of his own re-election as party leader,
the paper said.
   Bowing to opposition demands that his administration resign,
<PERSON>Motzfeldt</PERSON> set the vote for <DATE>March 5</DATE>.
   In the last ballot, in <DATE>May 1987</DATE>, <ORGANIZATION>Motzfeldt</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Siumut Party</ORGANIZATION> and
the non-socialist opposition <ORGANIZATION>Atassut Party</ORGANIZATION> each won 11 mandates in
the 16-seat Landsting, or homerule parliament.
   Siumut formed a coalition with the leftist Inuit Ataqatigiit
party, which has one mandate.
   The conservative-leaning <ORGANIZATION>Issittup Party</ORGANIZATION> has four.
</TEXT>
